VFestival of Sacred Music,&#8217; a carnival enriching carnatic music, was held at Thiruvaiyaru in Thanjavur district for three days from  February 27 to  March 1.The organisers of the festival, Prakiriti Foundation of Chennai, Marabu Foundation of Thillaisthanam near Thiruvaiyaru and Thanjavur chapter of the Indian National Trust for Art and Cultural Heritage (INTACH), chose the right locations to conduct the festival. The locations were southern praharam of Panchanatheeswaraswamy Temple, Pushya Mandapa Ghat and Rajah&#8217;s College both located on the banks of the River Cauvery.Besides choosing these heritage locations, Ranvir Shah, founder trustee of Prakiriti Foundation, took efforts to illuminate and decorate these places with the help of Kalai Selvan, technical expert and Praveen Kumar, a theatre personality from Chennai.The series started with the captivating vocal concert by Bombay Jayashree at Panchanatheeswaraswamy temple on February 27. Jayashree enthralled the audience with her attractive numbers.In the second programme at Pushya Mandapa Ghat on the banks of Cauvery on February 28,  Jayanthi Kumaresh entertained the audience with her veena recital. She was at her best when she played the famous &#8216;Kuraiyondrumillai,&#8217;  thillana and &#8216;Enna Thavam Seidhanai.&#8217; She said that playing in front of an enlightened audience at Tiruvaiyaru gave her immense satisfaction.The third programme at Rajah&#8217;s College, which showcased the melody of the flute played by Sikkil Sisters and Mala Chandrasekhar to a packed audience, went on well.  The trio  attracted the audience when they played &#8216;Chinnnanchiru Kiliye&#8217;  and &#8216;Katrinile Varum Geetham.&#8217;Ranvir Shah, said that the foundation, established in Chennai in 1997-98,  organised this festival to revive and enjoy our own heritage. He further said, &#8220;This is an attempt to discover Thiruvaiyaru in its original form. The foundation will conduct the festival at Thiruvaiyaru every year.&#8221;Rama Kausalya of Marabu foundation said that the festival  was aimed at reviving the glory of Thiruvaiyaru which  reverberated with music and dance in the olden days.&#8220;Pure Thiruvaiyaru handed over to us by our ancestors is now polluted due to our unhealthy practices. Besides restoring its old glory it is also our aim to improve its environment in places like Cauvery banks, old heritage sites, etc,&#8221; Kausalya said.S. N. M. Ubayathullah, State Commercial Taxes Minister, Babaji Rajah Bhonsle, Senior Prince of Thanjavur and Convenor of Thanjavur Chapter of INTACH, V. Gopalan and R. Mohan of Thiruvaiyaru Natyanjali Committee, Kumarasamy Thambiran of Dharmapuram Adheenam attended the festival.
